    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/12562</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Serbian Legation</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-05">December 5,
                            1918</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide Memoire</hi>
                </p>
                <p>On the request of the National Council (Slovenes, Croatians and Serbians) in
                    Zagreb the Serbian Government begs to bring to the knowledge of the United
                    States Government the unfriendly proceedings of the Italians in prohibiting the
                    importation of food stuffs, which will eventually force starvation upon the
                    population.</p>
                <p>The Italians have confiscated all merchandise in Rieka, and, quite recently, they
                    stopped two steamers at Kotor, laden with food, which were on their way from
                    Senj to Split, and took them to Italy.</p>
                <p>The purpose of this action on part of the Italians is to persuade the people in
                    Dalmatia and on the Croatian coast to declare themselves in favor of Italy.</p>
                <p>The Serbian Government anticipates that the United States Government will
                    favorably meet the request to do its utmost to curb the friction existing
                    between Italy and the National Council, and to use its great influence toward an
                    amicable settlement of the question.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
